Here's a basic example of a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that has a single slash command, `/ban`, which bans a mentioned user:

```javascript
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({
  intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages],
});

client.commands = new Map();

client.commands.set('ban', {
  name: 'ban',
  description: 'Bans a mentioned user',
  options: [
    {
      name: 'user',
      description: 'The user to ban',
      type: 'user',
      required: true,
    },
  ],
  execute: async (interaction) => {
    const member = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const memberTag = member.tag;
    const reason = 'No reason provided'; // You can add a way to provide a reason later

    await interaction.guild?.members.ban(member, { days: 7, reason: reason });
    await interaction.reply(`Banned ${memberTag} from the server.`);
  },
});

client.once('ready', () => {
  console.log('Bot is online!');
});

client.login('YOUR_DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN');

// Replace 'YOUR_DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN' with your actual bot token
```

Before running the code, make sure to:

1. Register your slash command: You can do this using the [Discord Developer Portal](https://discord.com/developers/applications). Create a command with the name `ban` and the options specified. You'll receive a `client_id` and `token` for your bot.
2. Install Discord.js: Run `npm install discord.js` or `yarn add discord.js` in your project directory.
3. Replace `YOUR_DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN` with your actual bot token.

Note: This code assumes you have the necessary permissions to ban members in the guilds the bot is a member of. Also, in a production-ready bot, you'd want to add error handling and possibly a more sophisticated way to provide the ban reason.

